## Comprehensive Guide to Understanding and Applying C++ Concepts

### Unit 3a

#### Basic Objects (Structs)
Structs in C++ are user-defined data types that group together variables under a single name. They are similar to classes but have all members public by default.

```cpp
struct Person {
    std::string name;
    int age;
};
```

#### Assignment of Objects
Objects of structs can be assigned directly if they have the same type.

```cpp
Person p1 = {"John", 30};
Person p2;
p2 = p1; // p2 now has the same values as p1
```

#### . and -> Operators
The `.` operator is used to access members of an object. The `->` operator is used to access members through a pointer to an object.

```cpp
Person p1 = {"John", 30};
p1.age = 31; // Using . operator

Person* p2 = &p1;
p2->age = 32; // Using -> operator
```

#### Use of `getline()`
`getline()` is used to read a line of text from an input stream.

```cpp
std::string line;
std::getline(std::cin, line);
```

#### Checking an Input Stream for Failure
You can check if an input stream has failed using the `fail()` method.

```cpp
std::cin >> value;
if (std::cin.fail()) {
    std::cerr << "Input failed!" << std::endl;
}
```

#### Using C++ String Class
The `std::string` class provides a convenient way to handle strings.

```cpp
std::string str = "Hello, World!";
str.append(" How are you?");
std::cout << str << std::endl;
```

### Unit 3b

#### Defining Your Own Classes
Classes in C++ are similar to structs but have more features like access specifiers and member functions.

```cpp
class Person {
public:
    std::string name;
    int age;
};
```

#### Public vs. Private
- **Public**: Members are accessible from outside the class.
- **Private**: Members are only accessible within the class.

```cpp
class Person {
private:
    int age;
public:
    std::string name;
    void setAge(int a) { age = a; }
    int getAge() { return age; }
};
```

#### Constructors and Destructors
- **Constructor**: Initializes an object.
- **Destructor**: Cleans up an object before it is destroyed.

```cpp
class Person {
public:
    std::string name;
    int age;

    Person(std::string n, int a) : name(n), age(a) {} // Constructor
    ~Person() {} // Destructor
};
```

#### Defining Member Functions
Member functions can be defined inside or outside the class.

```cpp
class Person {
public:
    std::string name;
    int age;

    void setAge(int a);
    int getAge();
};

void Person::setAge(int a) { age = a; }
int Person::getAge() { return age; }
```

#### Splitting Your Class into Files
You can split a class into a header file (`.h`) and a source file (`.cpp`).

**Person.h**
```cpp
#ifndef PERSON_H
#define PERSON_H

#include <string>

class Person {
public:
    std::string name;
    int age;

    Person(std::string n, int a);
    ~Person();
    void setAge(int a);
    int getAge();
};

#endif
```

**Person.cpp**
```cpp
#include "Person.h"

Person::Person(std::string n, int a) : name(n), age(a) {}
Person::~Person() {}
void Person::setAge(int a) { age = a; }
int Person::getAge() { return age; }
```

### Unit 4a

#### Linked Lists
A linked list is a linear data structure where each element is a separate object.

#### Implementing Basic Operations
- **Push**: Add an element.
- **Pop**: Remove an element.

```cpp
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* next;
};

class LinkedList {
public:
    Node* head;

    LinkedList() : head(nullptr) {}

    void push_front(int value) {
        Node* newNode = new Node{value, head};
        head = newNode;
    }

    void pop_front() {
        if (head) {
            Node* temp = head;
            head = head->next;
            delete temp;
        }
    }

    void push_back(int value) {
        Node* newNode = new Node{value, nullptr};
        if (!head) {
            head = newNode;
        } else {
            Node* temp = head;
            while (temp->next) {
                temp = temp->next;
            }
            temp->next = newNode;
        }
    }

    void pop_back() {
        if (!head) return;
        if (!head->next) {
            delete head;
            head = nullptr;
            return;
        }
        Node* temp = head;
        while (temp->next->next) {
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        delete temp->next;
        temp->next = nullptr;
    }
};
```

#### Efficiency of Various Operations
- **Push Front**: O(1)
- **Pop Front**: O(1)
- **Push Back**: O(n) without tail pointer, O(1) with tail pointer
- **Pop Back**: O(n) without tail pointer, O(1) with tail pointer

#### Pros and Cons Compared to Arrays
- **Pros**: Dynamic size, efficient insertions/deletions.
- **Cons**: More memory overhead, slower access time.

### Unit 4b

#### `vector<T>` and `deque<T>` Basic Operation
- **Vector**: Dynamic array with contiguous memory.
- **Deque**: Double-ended queue with efficient insertions/deletions at both ends.

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <deque>

std::vector<int> vec;
vec.push_back(1);
vec.pop_back();

std::deque<int> deq;
deq.push_back(1);
deq.pop_back();
deq.push_front(2);
deq.pop_front();
```

#### Efficiency of Their Operations
- **Vector**:
  - Push Back: Amortized O(1)
  - Pop Back: O(1)
  - Access: O(1)
- **Deque**:
  - Push Back/Front: O(1)
  - Pop Back/Front: O(1)
  - Access: O(1)

### Unit 4c

#### Doubly Linked Lists
A doubly linked list is a linked list where each node has a pointer to both the next and previous nodes.

#### Implementing Basic Operations
```cpp
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* next;
    Node* prev;
};

class DoublyLinkedList {
public:
    Node* head;
    Node* tail;

    DoublyLinkedList() : head(nullptr), tail(nullptr) {}

    void push_front(int value) {
        Node* newNode = new Node{value, head, nullptr};
        if (head) {
            head->prev = newNode;
        } else {
            tail = newNode;
        }
        head = newNode;
    }

    void pop_front() {
        if (head) {
            Node* temp = head;
            head = head->next;
            if (head) {
                head->prev = nullptr;
            } else {
                tail = nullptr;
            }
            delete temp;
        }
    }

    void push_back(int value) {
        Node* newNode = new Node{value, nullptr, tail};
        if (tail) {
            tail->next = newNode;
        } else {
            head = newNode;
        }
        tail = newNode;
    }

    void pop_back() {
        if (tail) {
            Node* temp = tail;
            tail = tail->prev;
            if (tail) {
                tail->next = nullptr;
            } else {
                head = nullptr;
            }
            delete temp;
        }
    }
};
```

#### Efficiency of Various Operations
- **Push Front/Back**: O(1)
- **Pop Front/Back**: O(1)

### Unit 4d

#### Multidimensional Arrays
Multidimensional arrays are arrays with more than one dimension.

#### Memory Layout of a Multidimensional Array
Multidimensional arrays are stored in row-major order in C++.

```cpp
int arr[2][3] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};
```

#### Passing Multidimensional Arrays to Functions
You can pass multidimensional arrays to functions by specifying the dimensions.

```cpp
void printArray(int arr[][3], int rows) {
    for (int i = 0; i < rows; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < 3; ++j) {
            std::cout << arr[i][j] << " ";
        }
        std::cout << std::endl;
    }
}

int main() {
    int arr[2][3] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};
    printArray(arr, 2);
    return 0;
}
```

### Unit 4e

#### Syntax and Use
References in C++ allow you to create an alias for another variable.

```cpp
int a = 10;
int& ref = a;
ref = 20; // a is now 20
```

#### Advantages of Passing by Reference
- **Efficiency**: No copying of data.
- **Modification**: Allows functions to modify the original variable.

#### Const References
Const references prevent the modification of the referenced variable.

```cpp
void printValue(const int& value) {
    std::cout << value << std::endl;
}

int main() {
    int a = 10;
    printValue(a);
    return 0;
}
```

### Unit 4f

#### Checking for Failure When Opening a File
You can check if a file was successfully opened using the `is_open()` method.

```cpp
std::ifstream inFile("input.txt");
if (!inFile.is_open()) {
    std::cerr << "Failed to open file!" << std::endl;
}
```

#### Using C++ `ifstream` and `ofstream` Classes for File I/O
- **ifstream**: Input file stream.
- **ofstream**: Output file stream.

```cpp
std::ifstream inFile("input.txt");
std::ofstream outFile("output.txt");

if (inFile.is_open() && outFile.is_open()) {
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(inFile, line)) {
        outFile << line << std::endl;
    }
    inFile.close();
    outFile.close();
}
```

#### Checking for Failure When Attempting to Receive Input
You can check if an input operation failed using the `fail()` method.

```cpp
int value;
std::cin >> value;
if (std::cin.fail()) {
    std::cerr << "Input failed!" << std::endl;
}
```

This comprehensive guide covers the essential concepts and provides detailed examples for each topic. Make sure to practice coding these examples to solidify your understanding.

